{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti** (Chapter 7) contains the most prominent moral vice-lists in the corpus: a \"tenfold group born of desire\" for kings (hunting, gambling, sleeping by day, slander, women, intoxication, song/dance/music, aimless wandering)[^1] and an \"eightfold group born of anger\" (malice, violence, treachery, envy, calumny, misappropriation of property, harshness of speech/punishment).[^2]\n\n**Bṛhaspati Smṛti** (Chapter 1) includes a shorter vice-list under \"The Vices of Women\": drinking, wandering, sleeping by day, and idleness.[^3]\n\nNo other works in the corpus contain comparable structured lists of moral vices (e.g., no matches for \"seven deadly sins,\" \"capital vices,\" or similar Western catalogues; scattered mentions of \"vice\" appear but lack list form).\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [p-afbfa2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-afbfa2).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [p-701061](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-701061) and [p-79fa07](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-79fa07).\n\n[^3]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, [p-6d8ba9](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-6d8ba9) and [p-2e7097](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-2e7097).",
